text: WOW.    Putting both the old and new versions side by side, you can instantly pinpoint the moment it turns absolutely facepalmingly retarded. The first movie is a classic because the jokes were witty, the movie had a realistic tone that we can all empathize with, and through it all, it had charm.  THIS movie is just another chance for our modern-day sex-obsessed society to get another few "laughs" at the expense of vulgarity, tired sex jokes, things getting set on fire, clichéd sleazy club music, and extremely annoying children. This trailer made me downright mad, and if you're one of the people praising this, you're obviously a millennial teenager that has never even heard of the original Vacation (like the teenager in this trailer), and deserves a slap in the side of the head.

Even the comedians of today don't have the same approach of the greatest comedians,  the cast from the 70s and 80s, such as Chase, but also Murray, Short, Candy, the list of goes on and on. Sadly, todays generation in their 20s and younger have no clue who these greats are. text: I'll be honest, I'm about to hate on this. If people wanna defend this by getting hostile, then I'm grown up enough to take it! This trailer gives the impression that the movie is childish, predictable and a low brow cash in on the original movie. If the trailer made the movie look good or original or atypical of the usual dirge spewed up by Hollywood executives, then I'd say 'yes, this is finally looking to be the sequel fans have been waiting for for 20 something years'. But it doesn't. I'll judge it when I see it obviously, and I'll keep an open mind. But this trailer isn't funny, and it doesn't bode well for the movie. If the movie is worthwhile, then I'll be satisfied, but I'm pretty sure my cynical outlook will become justified!

text: Looks like it will be WAY funnier than the original.  But while the actor playing Mr. Griswold seems to actually have more talent than Chevy Chase, I have to wonder whether his physical repulsiveness was a deliberate ploy by casting, to change the trajectory of the plot, or if it wasn't a mistake.  People watched Chase because he was (by Seventies standards) hot - really hot, despite his hair problems.  He oozed testosterone.  This actor is made even uglier by his up-do, and his massacred eyebrows.  Are his narrow shoulders and general air of impotence deliberately played-up?  It does work with his lines, which are HILARIOUS.   And the car is not as funny.  The original car was, like Chevy Chase, something essentially big, enviable, and beautiful, but with flaws.  This car is, like the new Griswold, just little and ugly.  But again, maybe this supports a different trajectory for the film, from that of the original.

text: For all you people that have been born ahead of 1995 and haven't had good enough parents to show you the original. This is a sort of remake/reboot/tribute of the 1983 movie National Lampoon's Vacation. It's following the original comedy vibe which made the first one so popular. This isn't just another Adam Sandler's Jack and Jill piece of shit. It's supposed to be like this so people like your parents can watch it and get a refreshing revamp of one of the best comedies from the 80's (when comedy was original and actually good IMO). I highly recommend everyone that hasn't seen it to check out the original. Its an absolute classic and one of the best comedies I've ever seen. It's what made all of the 90's, 00's, and 10's comedies what they are today. And you'll get basically all the references in this upcoming one if you do happen watch it.

text: You see it is funny because human beings do not normally gargle feces. Thus to have our protagonist do so creates _situational irony,_ and to have the audience be made aware of their folly ahead of time via the warning sign also creates _dramatic irony._ It also incidentally inspires in the audience a sense of bathos, as we are presented with a cast of characters who possess neither senses of smell nor senses of taste and consequently could not avoid the pitiable position in which they find themselves.  Truly, this scene shows an enviable grasp of classic dramatic techniques and their applications towards humorous ends.

text: 1ST ONE WAS RELEASED JULY 29TH 1983 THATS COOL. FUN FACT = Just like John Belushi, who starred in Animal House, Chevy Chase had previously performed in the National Lampoon Radio Hour and in the stage show National Lampoon Lemmings, both of which were spin-offs from National Lampoon magazine. In each of the main films of the series, the Griswold children are portrayed by different actors. This is usually attributed to the fact that after Anthony Michael Hall declined to reprise his role in European Vacation in order to star in Weird Science, it was decided to recast both children. Chase has indicated that it was his idea to continue recasting the children by explaining, "I always wanted to make the joke, 'Geez, I hardly ever get the chance to see the kids anymore. I hardly know who they are. We should go on a vacation.' That was funny to me: the idea that Clark was such a great family man, but still didn't even recognize his own children."

text: I'm fed up with all the elitist pricks saying "ohh this is a shit Hollywood reboot, this sucks, shit humour, the original is better" blah blah blah. First off this isn't a reboot, its just another installment, it's pretty much a sequel, it is Chevy Chases son grown up, having a vacation with his family. Secondly, the humour that made the first films food, is now overdone and they quite simply don't sell very well in the modern world. Sadly, what people seem to like these days is the potty humour, Ted, A Million Ways To Die In The West, Superbad, This Is The End ect. which I don't mind. With that being said, a lot of the humour in this movie is all referential, they are almost self aware of the other movies and decides to poke fun at that. As shown in the Ferrari clip at the end of the trailer.If you ignore that this is another installment, if you just stop comparing it to the first few movies and look at it as another modern day comedy movie, you will enjoy it a lot more. Give it a chance.

text: the trailers ruined any little entertainment value the movie has. I was so mad at myself for not listening to everyone about this movie. It was even shittier than I expected. apparently the movie had a budget of 30 mil and grossed over 100 mil. Very shocking. if there was such a thing as getting a refund for a movie after you saw it and then it would be erased from your memory.... this movie would have made zero! European Vacation was 10 times as entertaining as this, and we all know how bad that movie was. So predictable ( not just because of the trailers) because of bad writing. It was like watching a train wreck. As I watched it, I came up with so many ways that the movie could have been better or edited differently to make the movie watchable. I ended up being fixated on how they went wrong every couple minutes and how easily they could have made it better. They just went for the cheap predictable dick joke, or a little kid saying "fuck", or you name it. Comparing the original to this POS is like comparing a Frank Sinatra song to a Miley Cyris song. One is classic, the other should not exist. Who the fuck signed off on this movie and why did Chevy or Beverly ever want to be in this movie or associated with it?? My only assumption is that they either must be running out of money, had a deal they couldn't say no to, or they didn't get to see the whole script?? What the fuck is funny about Helms running into a steer on an ATV, killing it, then having Hemsworth hosing blood and guts off of him while another steer comes up to him and eats the blood and guts off the ground( i.e cannibalism)......then the family in the car the next scene making jokes about it??? What's a shameful movie.😞😞😞😞😞

text: As a filmmaker, I can shed some light for those of you who wonder how a group of people with functioning brains could possibly create such weak material. As laymen, I know you feel puzzled as to how a movie can be worse than what you could write if you drank too much, ate a bunch of alphabet soup and vomited on a bunch of blank script pages. It's not much of a mystery if you consider two factors. First, the Hollywood elite, including Chevy Chase and the rest of the cast and crew that have a stake in the originals, are morally corrupt. To them, kids swearing and raunchy comedy IS FUNNY. Second, the filmmakers KNEW THE FILM WAS HORRIBLE. THEY DIDN'T CARE. Bad, cheesy movies sadly have a target market, and are much cheaper to make. The filmmakers wanted a quick buck and knew they could spit out a film of bad quality that would find success because it was riding on the fame of the originals. They just wanted money. The sad part is this, the filmmakers spit on you as an audience. They knew you would expect it to be a quality film, knew they would get your bucks, and didn't care as they cut corners and pumped out easy to film crap so as to maximize their profits.  Now on the other hand, if they ACTUALLY WERE TRYING TO MAKE A GOOD FILM...................then holy crap are they stupid, because that film sucked. A camera falling down stairs would make a better film than that.

text: I really wanted to like the reboot of the classic Vacation, but I just can't. It's full of bad writing, terrible jokes and too many f bombs. It's not funny to have a young kid say fuck once, and it's even less funny the 20th time. Christina Applegate looks so bored and even a funny guy like Ed Helms falls flat. Even the cameo by the original Griswolds (Chevy Chase and Beverly D'Anglo) is a disappointment. Chevy looks so old and fat and poor Beverly only has about 3 lines. I'd rather watch European Vacation 10 times than watch this sorry remake.

text: Yes, this film did stand alone. Because unlike the original, it sucked. Come from a young millennial, I can assure you that the original was much funnier. They made the huge mistake of trying to make it bigger and better (and they failed). National Lampoon's Vacation was oddly very realistic and had a very real family atmosphere, while this one tried to be a modern day crazy childish comedy. Clark and Ellen had the real chemistry that you just don't see with Rusty and Debbie. Unlike the '83 version, this wasn't portrayed as being a real, relatable story. The classic was all "everything that could go wrong on your road trip" and the new is all "everything that could go wrong when you let 13 year old boys in the writing room".
author: Frankie Hernandez
